		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Latent+Heat">Latent Heat</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Latent+Heat">( 558884 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64231786"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64231786"><p>
Isn't one of the attributes of Deming/Toyota/Lean Manufacturing that you institute reliable processes rather than the Volkswagen Approach (at least as claimed in their 1960's commercials) of layering on inspections?
</p><p>
Some of this is also cultural in terms of giving assembly workers authority to stop the line if something is going wrong.
</p><p>
Yes, I am aware that airplanes don't exactly come off an assembly line, and especially for something aviation related, you need inspections.  And one should instill a "if<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

